Yes. The main issue is that you are mixing three different objectives that do not automatically align:
	1.	forecasting S_{t+1}, the next-day vol surface,
	2.	learning a useful discrete tokenizer/codebook, and
	3.	getting interpretable “states” from those codes.

A plain autoregressive prior can help with (1), but by itself it does not guarantee (3). In VQ-style models, the prior is trained to model the sequence of discrete tokens, not to make those tokens semantically aligned with human-meaningful regimes. The original VQ-VAE setup learns the codebook through reconstruction and then trains a separate prior over the discrete latents; the prior improves generation/forecasting, but interpretability has to be induced separately.  ￼

Your current diagnostics suggest the codebook is only partially healthy:
	•	codebook size = 32
	•	effective usage ≈ 17.7
	•	state accuracy = 16%

A perplexity / effective usage of about 17.7 out of 32 means you are not in catastrophic collapse, but you are also not using the full dictionary. In the VQ literature, lower perplexity is often treated as a sign of under-utilization or partial collapse, especially when it comes with poor downstream semantics.  ￼

The more important point is this: 16% state accuracy is not necessarily a failure unless your “state” target has around 6 classes. If you have:
	•	6 states, random chance is about 16.7%
	•	8 states, random chance is 12.5%
	•	10 states, random chance is 10%

So first benchmark your 16% against the class count and class imbalance. If it is near chance, then the codebook is not encoding your intended regime information, even if reconstruction or forecasting is decent.

What the prior is really doing

With an autoregressive Transformer prior, you would model something like

p(z_{t+1}\mid z_t, z_{t-1}, \dots)

or, if each surface is tokenized into multiple latent tokens,

p(z_{t+1,1},\dots,z_{t+1,M}\mid z_{\le t}, z_{t+1,<m})

This is good if your aim is:
	•	generate the next latent configuration,
	•	then decode it to the next surface,
	•	and capture temporal dependence in latent space.

That is exactly the kind of role the prior has in VQ-VAE: it learns structure over discrete latents after the autoencoder learns them.  ￼

But an autoregressive prior does not force code 7 to mean “high-skew panic regime” and code 12 to mean “calm short-dated carry regime.” It only learns transition probabilities between whatever latent symbols the encoder already emits.

So if the tokenizer is not already semantically organized, the Transformer prior will just become a very good model of opaque symbols.

The likely reason your state accuracy is low

There are a few common reasons.

1. Reconstruction objective dominates semantics

If the encoder-decoder is trained mainly to reconstruct or forecast the surface, the quantizer will partition the space according to whatever best reduces reconstruction error. That may be very local, geometric, and continuous, not regime-like.

For vol surfaces, the codebook may focus on:
	•	ATM level
	•	short-end term structure
	•	skew curvature
	•	local noise
	•	calendar/smile micro-shape

Those are useful for prediction, but they may not correspond to your chosen “states.”

2. One code is too local to represent a whole market regime

If each input gets mapped to one discrete code, that code has to carry everything:
	•	level
	•	slope
	•	skew
	•	curvature
	•	time dynamics
	•	exogenous conditions

That is often too much. In practice, discrete latent models frequently work better with multiple tokens or hierarchical latents, where one part captures coarse/global structure and another captures fine/local detail. Hierarchical variants were introduced precisely because a single flat codebook can fail to capture both global and local structure well.  ￼

3. Your “state” label may not be aligned with the unsupervised partition

If your labels are something like bull/bear/volatile/calm or hand-crafted regime IDs, the VQ model has no reason to recover those unless you explicitly encourage it.

4. Partial codebook collapse or shrinkage

Even moderate under-usage can hurt discriminative quality. Recent work continues to document dimensional/codebook collapse and token shrinkage as real issues in VQ systems.  ￼

My recommendation: do not let the prior carry the burden of interpretability

Use the prior for temporal modeling, but enforce interpretability at the tokenizer / codebook level.

The cleanest setup for your problem is:

Stage A — learn a good tokenizer

Encode surface S_t into discrete latent(s) z_t, decode back to either:
	•	S_t itself, or
	•	a representation of S_{t+1} if you want predictive tokenization.

But during this stage, add structure so codes become meaningful.

Stage B — train a temporal prior

Train a Transformer on token sequences:
z_{1:t} \to z_{t+1}

Then decode predicted z_{t+1} into forecasted surface.

That separation matches the classical VQ-VAE logic.  ￼

How to make the codebook interpretable

Here are the most effective interventions for your use case.

Option 1: supervise the codebook lightly

If you already have regime labels or state labels, attach a small head on top of:
	•	encoder output before quantization, and/or
	•	quantized embedding after quantization

and optimize:

\mathcal{L}
=
\mathcal{L}_{forecast}
+
\lambda_{vq}\mathcal{L}_{vq}
+
\lambda_{state}\mathcal{L}_{state}

This is usually the single most direct fix. Then the codebook is pressured to organize around your target states, instead of only reconstruction.

Option 2: separate global state token from local shape tokens

This is probably the best architectural move for vol surfaces.

Use:
	•	one global discrete token for regime/state
	•	several local tokens for surface geometry details

So:

z_t = (z_t^{global}, z_t^{local})

Then:
	•	interpret z_t^{global} as the state
	•	let z_t^{local} explain fine smile/term-structure variation

This is much better than expecting one flat codebook to do both jobs.

For vol surfaces, the global token can be encouraged to summarize:
	•	ATM level regime
	•	skew regime
	•	term-structure regime
	•	realized-vol / spot-vol context

while local tokens handle residual geometry.

Option 3: predict summary factors, not only the full surface

Make the code informative about low-dimensional risk factors:
	•	surface level
	•	term slope
	•	skew
	•	convexity/curvature
	•	short-end vs long-end spread

Add auxiliary losses for these factors. Then each code will tend to align with economically meaningful axes.

For your problem, this is extremely natural because traders already think in these factors.

Option 4: impose persistence or transition regularization on the state token

A regime/state should not jump randomly every day. So for the global token, add a temporal regularizer such as:
	•	persistence penalty,
	•	transition sparsity,
	•	Markov prior with sticky transitions,
	•	entropy control over transitions.

That often makes the codes look much more like real market regimes and much less like noisy clustering artifacts.

Should you use an autoregressive Transformer prior?

Yes, but I would use it in one of these two ways.

Setup 1: prior over global state token only

Train Transformer on the sequence of global state tokens:
p(z^{global}_{t+1}\mid z^{global}_{1:t}, x_{1:t}^{macro/features})

Then separately condition the local geometry forecast on the predicted global token.

This is the most interpretable version.

Setup 2: prior over global + local tokens

Train a Transformer over the full token set, but structure it so the global token is generated first:
p(z_{t+1}^{global}\mid \text{history}) \cdot p(z_{t+1}^{local}\mid z_{t+1}^{global}, \text{history})

This gives you:
	•	interpretable regime forecast first,
	•	then detailed surface refinement.

That is much better than treating all tokens symmetrically.

Why perplexity and state accuracy can disagree

Perplexity measures usage diversity, not semantic quality.

A codebook can have decent perplexity and still be useless for regime identification because the tokens may partition the space along nuisance directions. Conversely, a low-perplexity codebook might still be very predictive if only a few states truly matter.

So evaluate at least four things separately:
	•	reconstruction / forecast loss
	•	code usage / perplexity
	•	transition stability
	•	economic interpretability

For interpretability, inspect for each code:
	•	average surface
	•	average next-day surface change
	•	average ATM IV
	•	average skew
	•	average term slope
	•	realized return / realized vol around that code
	•	transition matrix between codes

That analysis is often more informative than raw “state accuracy.”

A very important concern in your current result

If your state accuracy is 16% and you want interpretable regimes, I would suspect one of these:
	•	your label definition is too noisy,
	•	your model is using the codebook for local reconstruction, not states,
	•	the codebook is too small or too flat,
	•	or the state head is trying to classify from the wrong representation.

A common improvement is to classify from the pre-quantized encoder representation while still quantizing for the decoder. If the pre-quantized latent has decent state accuracy but the quantized latent does not, then the quantizer is destroying the information you care about.

That is a very useful diagnostic.

Concrete path I would take for your volatility-surface project

I would not start with “one codebook + autoregressive Transformer prior + hope for interpretable states.”

I would do this:
	1.	Factorize the target
	•	global regime token
	•	local shape tokens
	2.	Add auxiliary supervised heads
	•	regime label
	•	ATM level bucket
	•	skew bucket
	•	term-slope bucket
	3.	Train tokenizer first
	•	reconstruct / forecast
	•	plus auxiliary state/factor losses
	4.	Then train Transformer prior
	•	forecast global token first
	•	forecast local tokens second
	5.	Audit each code
	•	average surface
	•	average deltas
	•	transition behavior
	•	persistence
	•	economic meaning

That gives you a much better shot at interpretability.

About codebook size 32

For a single global state token, 32 may actually be too many if you want human-readable regimes. You might end up with a fragmented state space. If you truly want interpretable regimes, I would often try:
	•	6
	•	8
	•	12
	•	16

for the global token, and reserve the richer capacity for local residual tokens.

In other words:
	•	small codebook for interpretable state
	•	larger codebook for geometry details

That tends to work better than asking one 32-codebook to do both.

Practical rule of thumb

If your goal is forecast accuracy, an autoregressive Transformer prior over VQ tokens is sensible.

If your goal is interpretable regimes, then:
	•	the prior is secondary,
	•	the tokenizer design and auxiliary objectives are primary.

That is the core design principle here.

My blunt assessment

Right now, your setup sounds like it is learning discrete compression units, not market states.

That is why:
	•	usage is middling,
	•	perplexity is not terrible,
	•	but state accuracy is weak.

The fix is not mainly “use a better prior.”
The fix is “make the latent variables represent the thing you want interpreted.”

